After reviewing which files include which other files, I have
determined that the proper place for the #defines are as follows: 


include/defs.h
   #ifndef BLOCK_C
   #   define NOT_BLOCK_C_CONST const
   #else
   #   define NOT_BLOCK_C_CONST
   #endif

src/block.c
   ...
   #define BLOCK_C 1
   ...
   #include "whatever (didn't write that part down).h"
   ...
   Prototype NOT_BLOCK_C_CONST Block ActualBlock;
   Block ActualBlock = { NULL, BT_NONE, ...whatever

I tried this last night and it works well.  The compiler behaves as it
should and refuses to compile modules other than block.c which try to
change fields in ActualBlock.  All the functions I had been using to
read fields in ActualBlock have been changed back to references, and
the code is beautiful and clean again. 


I highly recommend this technique for other modules with global
visible data with semantics which need to be controlled.

A couple of other functions that have proven quite handy:
  Column block_leftcolumn( Line line) and
  Column block_rightcolumn(Line line)
They return the left- or right-most column the block covers
on the given line, or -1 if the block does not extend to that line.

